JOHANNESBURG - A lower inflation outlook could result in interest rate cuts later in 2018. While the latest figures from Statistics South Africa show consumer price inflation (CPI) increased slightly at the end of 2017, prices in December grew more slowly than expected at 4.7 percent. The hefty petrol price hike was the main driver behind this. READ:Â What the strong rand means for you But with fuel price cuts in January and another drop expected in February, inflation is expected to continue its downward trend. Food price growth has also continued to ease. On January 18, the Reserve Bank kept interest rates steady with the repo rate at 6.25 percent and banks' lending rate at 10.25 percent. eNCA